        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What does "local SEO automation" actually mean?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>It means software (or a managed service) handles the repetitive local SEO work without an operator clicking through every step. The typical surface: GBP posts, citation submissions, review request flows, review response drafts, rank scans, and local landing page generation. Real automation removes the click.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I automate everything in local SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Local search is high-trust — you cannot fully auto-respond to negative reviews or auto-generate every GBP post without quality slipping. The right model is automation for the repetitive 80% and human attention for the 20% that needs judgement.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between an automation tool and an agency?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>An automation tool gives you a dashboard and you still own strategy and execution. A managed service like theStacc owns both — you write a brief, they ship the work. Tool plus your time is rarely cheaper than the service if you cost your time honestly.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is autonomous-agent local SEO actually working in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Autonomous agents (Paige, OTTO) handle a meaningful chunk of GBP optimisation without an operator. They are best at posts, Q&amp;A, photo updates, and basic schema. They are weakest at strategy. Pair them with a human, do not replace one.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How much should I expect to pay for local SEO automation?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Self-serve automation tools run $20–$100/mo per location. Managed services that include automation plus content sit at $150–$500 per location. Enterprise platforms range from $300 to $1,000+. Most single-location operators land around $50 to $200 all-in.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Will automated GBP posts hurt my ranking?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Not if they are useful posts. Google does not penalise scheduled posts — it penalises spammy, low-quality posts. The risk with automation is template fatigue: same post format, same offer, every week. Mix templates with operator-written posts.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should I automate review responses?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Automate the request flows. Draft the responses with AI. Do not auto-publish replies, especially on negative reviews — a wrong word on Google compounds into a reputation problem. The safest pattern is AI-drafted, human-approved.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

